In defense of these particular critics, they’re not historians or legal experts, they’re political commentators. That’s why engaging with the relevant historical literature and case law is so important. But thanks for reading!

To such a degree that c2, which contains the “good faith” takedown provision, basically becomes obsolete. I cite a couple of cases that trace this evolution. And I also cite Justice Thomas’ superb opinion in the Malwarebytes case that sets out the analysis - worth reading

As to Section 230, the @WIRED write up in particular takes me to task for allegedly getting the “good faith” provision wrong. But the reviewer doesn’t appear to have read or understood the relevant cases, which walk through the courts’ expansion of Section 230c1

Even though TR gave too much ground on monopoly, the TR-Wilson battle still matters because TR remained a defender of republican political economy. Wilson abandoned it. Efforts to rein in monopoly that aren’t linked to republican ideals won’t rescue self government

This new pro-corporate consensus. I take Theodore Roosevelt to task in the book for getting too comfortable w/ monopoly power himself. The corporate liberal consensus has informed our politics for decades. And no, FDR didn’t fundamentally alter the balance, as I mention in book

His antitrust reforms in fact ultimately helped cement the new corporate liberal consensus, w/ a big assist from the Supreme Court. Again, there’s an extensive secondary literature on this for those who care to read. And my argument is that both left AND right basically accepted

Wilson changed his rhetoric for a period in 1912, to try to contrast himself with Theodore Roosevelt. I talk about this in the book. But the conversion was mostly rhetorical, and fleeting. Wilson never became a Brandeisian

That’s lazy. Do the work. Take the time to understand the historical debate & engage with it. I stand by my analysis of Wilson’s writings and speeches over the decades of his career. The guy was comfortable with bigness & corporatism

I think these historians are largely correct, and I cite some of the extensive secondary literature in the book. My lefty critics, however, don’t engage with any of this historical debate or even seem aware of it. They claim that calling Wilson a corporatist is a factual “error”

There is some irony here. The fiercest critics of Wilson as a corporatist come from progressive historians, who have argued for decades now that Wilson was basically okay w/ monopoly power & corporate power more generally

A few further thoughts on the lefty unease with history on display in the @WIRED and @newrepublic write ups of my book. These folks try to take me to task for calling Woodrow Wilson a corporatist, a position the authors appear to dislike because Wilson was a Democrat
